  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has evolved significantly over the past several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a concept in response to organized crime activities in the 1920s-1930s\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities like bootlegging and gambling\n\n2. Initial Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Legislation:\n- United States Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First comprehensive legislative attempt to combat money laundering\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Mandated record-keeping for financial transactions\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created recommendations for global financial regulations\n\n4. Major Expansion:\n- United States Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Made money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- Significantly expanded legal mechanisms to prosecute financial crimes\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced AML regulations\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing\n- Expanded reporting and monitoring requirements\n\n6. Ongoing Global Standardization:\n- Continuous refinement of international AML frameworks\n- Increased cooperation between countries\n- More sophisticated tracking and detection mechanisms\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve with technological and financial innovations.",
